## Why the formatting conventions matter here

The `═══` headers and `━━━` separators are not decoration. In a no-code platform, your executor is parsing or chunking this output to feed downstream agents. Consistent delimiters mean you can split the output by file reliably, extract the "MUST_READ_FULLY" list with a simple pattern, and know exactly where the synthesis section begins. Without them, you're doing regex on prose — fragile and error-prone.

The negative examples (`BAD GOTCHA` / `GOOD GOTCHA`, `BAD EXAMPLE` / `GOOD EXAMPLE`) are equally important. They set the quality floor. Without them, the agent satisfies the letter of the instruction with the laziest valid output. With them, it has a calibration signal.

The `WHAT AGENT 3 MUST NOT DO` section at the end is the piece most people leave out. It's the difference between a planner that produces clean, minimal changes and one that goes wide and creates a mess.
